Luxembourg: A more than 100-year-legal ban on abortion was lifted in Luxembourg in 2009, but little has changed in its implementation. The practice is still taboo in this Catholic country in the westernmost part of Belgium, Britain, and the Netherlands. Only 13 percent of residents in a 2014 survey by the country’s health ministry agreed with the idea that abortion is a right. And despite its new legalization, one in three women still admit to having an abortion before its legal age [9]. Norway: Abortion is generally accessible and women have the right to receive care in perfect confidentiality merely by informing doctors or midwives of their desire to terminate the pregnancy. Abortions are legal up to the 21st week of pregnancy, provided the woman gives free consent to the procedure. There are exceptions, such as when it is necessary to protect the life or health of the woman, in cases of rape, and in fetal genetic deformation.
